This article provides a list of formal corruption allegations against [[Parliament of Ghana|Ghanaian parliamentarians]], sorted from most recent date to least recent.
*'''[[Abuga Pele]]'''. Member of parliament for the Chiana-Paga constituency, Abuga pele was convicted in February 2018 and charged with a six-year jail term for willfully causing a loss of GH¢4.1 million to the state of Ghana.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pulse.com.gh/news/politics/allegations-here-are-the-politicians-accused-of-corrupt-practices-in-ghana-id7417339.html|title=Allegations: Here are the politicians accused of corrupt practices in Ghana|last=Tornyi|first=Emmanuel|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Abuga-Pele-prayed-for-lesser-jail-term-because-he-was-MP-629348|title=Abuga Pele prayed for lesser jail term because he was MP|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2018-06-05}}</ref> *'''[[Mubarak Mohammed Muntaka|Mohammed Mubarak Muntaka]]'''. In June 2009, Mubarak Muntaka resigned from his position as Minister of Youth and Sports on the orders of president Mills following investigations into dozens of allegations leveled against him including financial malpractice and abuse of power. Ghana's [[Commission on Human Rights and Administrative Justice]] asked Mubarak Muntaka to refund misappropriated funds.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.modernghana.com/news/306541/girl-not-muntakas-lover.html|title=Girl Not Muntaka's Lover|work=Modern Ghana|access-date=2018-06-02|language=en-gb}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/crime/Kwesi-Pratt-Muntaka-Cannot-Be-Free-164486|title=Kwesi Pratt: Muntaka Cannot Be Free|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2018-06-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.modernghana.com/news/258814/muntaka-for-chraj-over-girlfriend.html|title=Muntaka For CHRAJ Over Girlfriend|work=Modern Ghana|access-date=2018-06-05|language=en-gb}}</ref> *'''[[Mahama Ayariga]]'''. The Commission on Human Rights and Administrative Justice was petitioned by a pressure group in September 2009 to investigate Mahama Ayariga for acquiring 5 subsidized tractors from the ministry of Agriculture that were meant to support underprivileged farmers in rural communities. Appointments Committee of Parliament initially suspended his approval of becoming a minister pending investigations, that cleared him afterwards.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201002160999.html|title=Ghana: Minority Tightens Noose on Ayariga|last=Odoi-Larbi|first=Stephen|date=2010-02-16|work=Ghanaian Chronicle (Accra)|access-date=2018-06-05}}</ref> Mahama Ayariga claimed that his application to acquire the tractors "was approved" and he was unaware that there was an "affordable arrangements" scheme associated with purchasing the tractors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Ayariga-I-am-innocent-in-purchase-of-tractors-169776|title=Ayariga: I am innocent in purchase of tractors|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2018-06-05}}</ref> The investigation was reopened in July 2017 when a different political party formed a new government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/Mahama-ministers-hot-as-names-of-former-appointees-under-investigation-pop-up-562115|title=Mahama ministers hot as names of former appointees under investigation pop up|website=www.ghanaweb.com|language=en|access-date=2018-06-05}}</ref> <!--* Okudzeto Ablakwa, former deputy education minister *[[Dzifa Ativor]], former transport minister (bus branding) *[[Alban Bagbin]], former works and housing minister *[[Asiedu Nketia|Aseidu Nketia]], NDC general secretary * Hannah Bissiw, former deputy works and housing minister-->
