{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}} {{Infobox ethnic group | group = Wakhi | image = Shaila.jpg | caption = A Wakhi girl from the village of Zood Khun, [[Chiporsun|Chapursan Valley]], [[Pakistan]]. | pop = ~ 50,000–58,000<ref name="britannica">{{cite encyclopedia |url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Iranian-languages |title=Iranian languages |encyclopedia=Encyclopædia Britannica |access-date=14 July 2018}}</ref><ref name="ethnologue">{{cite web |url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/wbl |title=Wakhi |work=Ethnologue |access-date=14 July 2018}}</ref> | popplace = [[Afghanistan]], [[China]], [[Pakistan]], [[Tajikistan]] | langs = [[Wakhi language|Wakhi]] | rels = [[Islam]] ([[Isma'ilism|Ismaili Shia]]) }} The '''Wakhi people''', or the '''Khik''',<ref name="Hermann">{{cite journal|last=Kreutzmann|first=Hermann|date=3 September 2003|title=Ethnic minorities and marginality in the Pamirian Knot: survival of Wakhi and Kirghiz in a harsh environment and global contexts|journal=The Geographical Journal|publisher=Blackwell Publishing|volume=169|pages=215–235}}</ref> are an [[ethnic group]] living in adjacent, remote regions of [[Afghanistan]], [[Tajikistan]], [[Pakistan]], and [[China]]. They are predominantly centered in Afghanistan's [[Wakhan Corridor]], the northern-most part of Pakistan's [[Gilgit-Baltistan]], the [[Gorno-Badakhshan Autonomous Region|Gorno-Badakhshan]] region of Tajikistan, and the southwestern region of China's [[Xinjiang]].<ref name="el">{{cite web|url=http://elalliance.org/languages/iranic/wakhi/|title=Wakhi|work=Endangered Language Alliance|access-date=14 July 2018}}</ref> They are native speakers of [[Wakhi language|Wakhi]], an [[Indo-European languages|Indo-European language]] of the [[Iranian languages|Iranian branch]].
== Name == The Wakhi people refer to themselves as ''Khik'' and to their language as ''Khik zik''.<ref name="Hermann" /> The [[Exonym and endonym|exonym]] ''Wakhī'', which is given to them by their neighbors, is based on ''Wux̌'', the local name of the region of [[Wakhan]], deriving from *''Waxšu'', the old name of the [[Amu Darya|Oxus River]] (Amu Darya), which is a major river formed by the junction of the [[Vakhsh River|Vakhsh]] and [[Panj River|Panj]] rivers on the border between Tajikistan and Afghanistan.<ref name="britannica" />
== Demographics == [[File:Wakhan,_Badakhshan.jpg|thumb|The [[Wakhan Corridor]] under light snow, with a Wakhi man collecting firewood.]] [[File:Gulmit_-_GB_-_04_-_Nasr_Rahman.jpg|thumb|Wakhi musicians in [[Gulmit]], [[Gilgit-Baltistan]], [[Pakistan]].]] Ethnic Wakhi-speakers have a total population of about 50,000–58,000.<ref name="britannica" /><ref name="ethnologue" /> The population is divided between four countries: [[Afghanistan]], [[Tajikistan]], [[Pakistan]], and [[China]]'s [[Xinjiang]]. Due to wars, heavy taxation, and oppression by the local rulers, the Wakhi people have migrated south to form the Wakhi settlements present today in northwestern Pakistan.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Shafiq|first1=Nadeem|title=The Wakhi Community Settlements in Northern Pakistan|journal=Journal of Political Studies|page=1|quote=The major Wakhi Community settlements in Pakistan are found in Chitral and Gilgit-Baltistan areas. Their ancestors fled to these regions due to a couple of reasons including wars, heavy taxation and oppression by the local rulers and Afghan officials.}}</ref>
In China, the Wakhi people, together with the [[Sarikoli language|Sarikoli people]], are officially recognized as "[[Tajiks of Xinjiang|Tajiks]]", with ethnic-minority autonomous status. In Afghanistan, they are officially called "[[Pamiris|Pamiri]]". In Tajikistan, they are recognized by the state as "Tajiks", but self-identify as "Pamiri". In Pakistan, they refer to themselves as "Pamiri" or "[[Gojal|Gujali]]".{{cn|date=July 2018}}
The Wakhi predominantly adhere to [[Nizari]] [[Isma'ilism|Ismaili]] [[Shia Islam]], which is regarded as their [[ethnic religion]], and are followers of the [[Aga Khan IV|Aga Khan]].<ref name="Hermann" /><ref name="West, Barbara 2008">{{cite book|title=Encyclopedia of the Peoples of Asia and Oceania|last=West|first=Barbara|publisher=Facts on File|year=2008|ISBN=0816071098}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p6aXloa1QsEC|title=The Kirghiz and Wakhi of Afghanistan|last=Shahrani|first=M. Nazif Mohib|publisher=University of Washington Press|year=2002|ISBN=0-295-98262-4|location=Seattle|page=216}}</ref>
== Economy == The Wakhi are primarily nomadic, depending on their herds of yaks and horses.<ref name="KPK=PT">{{cite web|url=http://www.khyberpakhtunkhwa.gov.pk/aboutus/People-Tribles.php|title=Khyber Pakhtunkhwa: People and Tribes|work=Government of the Khyber Pakhtunkhwa|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150316183221/http://www.khyberpakhtunkhwa.gov.pk/aboutus/People-Tribles.php|archivedate=16 March 2015|deadurl=no}}</ref> They often have two residences—one for winter and one for summer. Their houses are built of stone and sod.<ref name="Hermann" />
== Cultural preservation == Activists and researchers have been working to preserve and record the language of the Wakhi people, and have developed Wakhi orthographies using the Arabic, Cyrillic, and Latin scripts.<ref name="el" />
In 1990, the Gojali Wakhis of Pakistan established the "Wakhi Tajik Cultural Association", which aimed to preserve, document, and publish their "local culture". The association introduced a script that was applied into linguistic and literary textbooks, and organized cultural festivals. [[Radio Pakistan]]'s Radio Gilgit also aired a daily Wakhi-language program named ''Bam-e Dunya'' ("Roof of the World").<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hqwYDQAAQBAJ|title=Disappearing Peoples?: Indigenous Groups and Ethnic Minorities in South and Central Asia|last1=Brower|first1=Barbara|last2=Johnston|first2=Barbara Rose|date=2016|publisher=Routledge|page=184}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C7au4-y3Q-AC|title=The Iranian Languages|last=Windfuhr|first=Gernot|date=2013|publisher=Routledge|page=826}}</ref>
